subSubSection.paragraph:
Head
. Antenna four-segmented, geniculate (
Figs 2A
, 
4A
); first article thin, evenly widened apically, long, length approximately equal to that of three remaining articles combined; second article rounded; third article cylindrical with proximal portion narrowed; second and third article short, with about one fourth of first article length; fourth article elongated, subequal in length to the second article, tapering apically (
Fig. 4A
). Articles covered with scattered, pointed setae (
Fig. 4A
). Labium three-segmented. Coiled stylets visible in diaphanized specimens.
